Finally, combine the 'cut' item and the 'finely cut' item, and then frame the resulting combined item. This sequence consistently yields 100 points.

message: To reach 100 points: First, cut any 'natural, soft' ingredient (e.g., sunflower, mushroom) once, it will be worth 25 points and gain the 'cut' feature. Second, cut any 'artificial, soft' ingredient (e.g., ribbon, yarn, sponge, newspaper, cardboard) once, it will also be worth 25 points and gain the 'cut' feature. Third, combine these two 'cut' items (one natural, one artificial), which will result in an 80-point item. Finally, use the 'frame' tool on this combined 80-point item to reach 100 points. Be aware that 'hard' ingredients initially give negative values when cut once, but a second cut with scissors makes them 'finely cut' and worth 25 points. However, combinations of hard and soft items, or two soft items of the same type, typically yield less (50 points) before framing, resulting in 70 points after framing. Do NOT combine items that have already been framed, as this leads to a significant loss of value.

message: To achieve 100 points, understand the cutting rules: 1. Soft items (natural or artificial) become 'cut' and gain 25 points with one scissor use. 2. Hard items (natural or artificial) become '-30' after one cut, but a second cut with scissors makes them 'finely cut' and worth 25 points. To reach 100, combine two 25-point cut items that are *different* in their 'natural/artificial' property (e.g., 'cut artificial-soft' + 'cut natural-soft' OR 'finely cut artificial-hard' + 'finely cut natural-hard'). This combined item will be worth 80 points. Then, use the 'frame' tool on this 80-point item to increase its value to 100. Combining items that share both 'natural/artificial' and 'soft/hard' properties (e.g., two 'artificial-soft, cut' items) only yields 50 points, which frames to 70.

message: To reach 100 points, aim to create a 'finely cut' or 'regularly cut' item from ingredients. Soft items (flower, yarn) usually become 'cut' (25 points) after one use of scissors. Hard items (bark, beads) become 'cut' (-30 points) after one use of scissors, but 'finely cut' (25 points) after a second use of scissors. Combine two 'cut' or 'finely cut' items, ensuring they have diverse features (e.g., natural/artificial, soft/hard), to get an 80-point item. Combining items with similar features might only yield 50 points. Finally, use the 'frame' tool on your 80-point combined item to reach 100 points. Good luck!
